 src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the origional Roman empires Still ruled the worl</span><hr size=1> I think we should consider that the Roman Empire not collapsing could have been a great setback for civilization.<br>
<br>
It has already been noted that such inventions as the balloon, steam power and effective telegraphy were either overlooked or regarded as mere curiosities by the Romans.  To this list many more can be added.<br>
<br>
There is no guarantee that the Romans would not have simply entered the same kind of introverted, self-obsessed stagnation that China has practiced so successfully for the past several thousand years, ending only in the middle of the last century.<br>
<br>
China has had the time and the resources to conquer the Earth, and indeed the entire solar system if they had progressed faster, for thousands of years, yet they have done nothing but get smacked around like the west's little bitch.<br>
<br>
The birth of modern western civilization lies in the Renaissance, which occurred in the unique social and political environment of middle ages Italy, it is doubtful that, this could have occurred at any other time and place.<br>
<br>
The gifts of the renaissance are the scientific method, reason, self-examination, a strong emphasis on independence and liberty and an almost relentless curiosity and thirst for progress.<br>
<br>
Despite the fact that the fall of the Roman Empire set back technology and civilization 1000 years, and then let us languish in darkness for another 1000, I find it hard to belive that the stodgy and complacent Romans could have come as far in last 1500 years, as we have in the last 500, even with their head start.<br>
